client_background:
Vision: We give people the confidence to become active citizens, to support each other, to alleviate social isolation, and provide the opportunity for individual self-expression, social interaction and personal achievement.  
Customers: Our users are residents of Kensington and surrounding areas, including but not limited to:
- Families and seniors living in public housing;
- People from culturally and linguistically diverse backgrounds;
- Children aged 18 months to 5 years attending child care (and their parents/carers);
- Primary and Secondary school children;
- Adult learners
- People experiencing social isolation;
- People on low incomes;
- Conversely, we also provide programs for many high income/time poor community members. 

Stakeholders include Federal, State and Local Government departments, partner organisations, other community agencies

Products: Please refer to our website for all programs. In summary:
- Morning child care;
- Homework Clubs
- Adult English classes and vocational training;
- Art, Cooking, Environment courses;
- Recreation and exercise programs;
- Social programs;
- After-school programs for children;
- Volunteer opportunities

Competitors: We don't really have any. We work collaboratively with other Neighbourhood Houses in our areas. In general terms, there is competition from:
- Long day care and family day care operators;
- Organisations like Laneway Learning or the CAE (for short courses); 
Business Model: Kensington Neighbourhood House is an incorporated association. It is community owned and community run (volunteer Board of Management). It is a not-for-profit registered with the ACNC.

We receive operational funds from:
- Federal Government (Department of Education)
- State Government (Department of Education, Department of Families, Fairness & Housing
- Local Government (City of Melbourne)
- Fees from participants

We augment the above with grant funding from all levels of government, industry and philanthropic funds. 
Challenges: - (Ignoring Covid), Kensington Neighbourhood House is a dynamic and thriving organisation. However, our users skew towards the very young (and their families) and people over 55. We tend not to attract/reach a younger audience (25 - 45). 
- Facebook is our only social media channel (largely because our staff are over 50 and this is the only channel we know how to use!)
- We want to know other social media avenues for attracting participants to our courses and programs.

